08352nam a22010815i 9780812204865DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122048657 a10.9783/97808122048652doi  a(DE-B1597)449340  a(OCoLC)979904817  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM42b.J485 2011eb 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.07122200aJewish Studies at the Crossroads of Anthropology and History :bAuthority, Diaspora, Tradition /ced. by Ra'anan S. Boustan, Marina Rustow, Oren Kosansky. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b16 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Anthropology, History, and the Remaking of Jewish Studies -- tPART I. AUTHORITY -- tChapter 1. “How Do You Know That I Am a Jew?”: Authority, Cultural Identity, and the Shaping of Postwar American Judaism -- tChapter 2. Rabbis and Their (In)Famous Magic: Classical Foundations, Medieval and Early Modern Reverberations -- tChapter 3. Dreamers in Paradise: The Rise and Fall of a New Holy Site in Beit She’an, Israel -- tChapter 4. Words, Images, and Magic: The Protection of the Bride and Bridegroom in Jewish Marriage Contracts -- tPART II. DIASPORA -- tChapter 5. The Dislocation of the Temple Vessels: Mobile Sanctity and Rabbinic Rhetorics of Space -- tChapter 6. Sacred Space, Local History, and Diasporic Identity: The Graves of the Righteous in Medieval and Early Modern Ashkenaz -- tChapter 7. Detours in a “Hidden Land”: Samuel Romanelli’s Masa’ ba‘rav -- tChapter 8. The Rhetoric of Rescue: “Salvage Immigration” Narratives in Israeli Culture -- tPART III. TRADITION -- tChapter 9. Judaism and Tradition: Continuity, Change, and Innovation -- tChapter 10. In the Path of Our Fathers: On Tradition and Time from Jerusalem to Babylonia and Beyond -- tChapter 11. Prayer, Literacy, and Literary Memory in the Jewish Communities of Medieval Europe -- tChapter 12. A Temple in Your Kitchen: Hafrashat H˙ allah—The Rebirth of a Forgotten Ritual as a Public Ceremony -- tChapter 13. Judaism and the Idea of Ancient Ritual Theory -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past several decades, the field of Jewish studies has expanded to encompass an unprecedented range of research topics, historical periods, geographic regions, and analytical approaches. Yet there have been few systematic efforts to trace these developments, to consider their implications, and to generate new concepts appropriate to a more inclusive view of Jewish culture and society. Jewish Studies at the Crossroads of Anthropology and History brings together scholars in anthropology, history, religious studies, comparative literature, and other fields to chart new directions in Jewish studies across the disciplines.This groundbreaking volume explores forms of Jewish experience that span the period from antiquity to the present and encompass a wide range of textual, ritual, spatial, and visual materials. The essays give full consideration to non-written expressions of ritual performance, artistic production, spoken narrative, and social experience through which Jewish life emerges. More than simply contributing to an appreciation of Jewish diversity, the contributors devote their attention to three key concepts—authority, diaspora, and tradition—that have long been central to the study of Jews and Judaism. Moving beyond inherited approaches and conventional academic boundaries, the volume reconsiders these core concepts, reorienting our understanding of the dynamic relationships between text and practice, and continuity and change in Jewish contexts. More broadly, this volume furthers conversation across the disciplines by using Judaic studies to provoke inquiry into theoretical problems in a range of other areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthorityvReligious aspectsvJudaism. 0aAuthorityxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aJewish diaspora. 0aJewsvStudy and teaching. 0aJewsxStudy and teaching. 0aJudaismvStudy and teaching. 0aJudaismxStudy and teaching. 0aRELIGIONvJudaismxHistory. 0aTradition (Judaism). 4aJewish Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.1 aBaumgarten, Albert I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilu, Yoram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoustan, Ra'anan S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoustan, Ra‘anan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChajes, J. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Or, Tamar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Harvey E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Sylvie Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanarfogel, Ephraim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatriel, Tamar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosansky, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosansky, Oren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrell, Riv-Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaspe, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRustow, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRustow,